tle Saxham, Suffolk, England":"Little Saxham, Suffolk, England","Mildenhall, Suffolk, England":"Mildenhall, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Risby","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Risby in Walesby (Lincolnshire), Risby in Roxby cum Risby (Lincolnshire), Risby (Suffolk), or Risby in Rowley (East Yorkshire). The Lincolnshire placenames probably derive from Old Norse <i>hrís</i> ‘brushwood’ + <i>bý</i> ‘farmstead, village’. The East Yorkshire placename probably derives from Old Norse <i>ryth</i> (genitive <i>rytz</i>) ‘clearing’ + <i>bý</i>. The Suffolk placename may derive from Old Norse <i>hrís</i> or <i>ryth</i> + <i>bý</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Amy","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of Old French <i>Amee</i> ‘beloved’. This originated in part as a vernacular nickname, in part as a form of Latin <i>Amata</i>. The latter is ostensibly the feminine form of the past participle of <i>amare</i> ‘to love’, but in fact it may have had a different, pre-Roman, origin; it was borne in classical mythology by the wife of  King Latinus , whose daughter  Lavinia  married  Aeneas  and (according to the story in the <i>Aeneid</i>) became the mother of the Roman people."],"variants":[{"name":"Aimie","meanings":["Anglicized form of Old French <i>Amee</i> ‘beloved’. This originated in part as a vernacular nickname, in part as a form of Latin <i>Amata</i>. The latter is ostensibly the feminine form of the past participle of <i>amare</i> ‘to love’, but in fact it may have had a different, pre-Roman, origin; it was borne in classical mythology by the wife of  King Latinus , whose daughter  Lavinia  married  Aeneas  and (according to the story in the <i>Aeneid</i>) became the mother of the Roman people."]},{"name":"Aimée","meanings":["originally a vernacular nickname meaning ‘beloved’, from the past participle of French <i>aimer</i> ‘to love’ (Latin <i>amare</i>;  compare  Amy  ). It has been in use in French since the Middle Ages, although it has never been very common. It is now also used, with or without the accent, as a given name in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Amie","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Amy  , corresponding in form to the French vocabulary word meaning ‘(female) friend’."]},{"name":"Ami","meanings":["Anglicized form of Old French <i>Amee</i> ‘beloved’. This originated in part as a vernacular nickname, in part as a form of Latin <i>Amata</i>. The latter is ostensibly the feminine form of the past participle of <i>amare</i> ‘to love’, but in fact it may have had a different, pre-Roman, origin; it was borne in classical mythology by the wife of  King Latinus , whose daughter  Lavinia  married  Aeneas  and (according to the story in the <i>Aeneid</i>) became the mother of the Roman people."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Dev ."],"variants":[{"name":"Deborah","meanings":["Biblical name (meaning ‘bee’ in Hebrew), borne by the nurse of Rebecca (Genesis 35:8) and by a woman judge and prophet (Judges 4–5) who led the Israelites to victory over the Canaanites. It has always been popular as a Jewish name. It was in use among Christians by the mid 16th century and was taken up by the Puritans in the 17th century, in part because the bee was a symbol of industriousness. Since then it has enjoyed enormous popularity, peaking in the 1960s. Among other famous bearers is the actress  Deborah Kerr  (  1921–2007 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":2,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":47,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Amy de Risby was born about 1335, in Mildenhall, Suffolk, England, her father, Phillip de Risby, was 19 and her mother, Anne, was 14. She married John Hethe about 1353, in Mildenhall, Suffolk, England. They were the parents of at least 6 sons. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"about 1335–":"umbes 1335–Surnud","1335–Female":"1335–Surnud","–1374":"–1374","1335–1392":"1335–1392","1360–1397":"1360–1397","1360–1440":"1360–1440","1378–Male":"1378–Surnud","1380–1428":"1380–1428","–1383":"–1383","–1415":"–1415","1317–Male":"1317–Surnud","1322–Female":"1322–Surnud","1440":"1440","1374":"1374","1383":"1383","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1392":"1392","1380":"1380","1415":"1415","1337":"1337","Abt 1360":"umbes 1360","1335":"1335","1378":"1378","1322":"1322","1453":"1453","1342":"1342","1397":"1397","about 1335":"umbes 1335","about 1353":"umbes 1353","1428":"1428","1317":"1317","Little Saxham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Little Saxham, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Little Saxham, Suffolk, England":"Little Saxham, Suffolk, England","Mildenhall, Suffolk, England":"Mildenhall, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1335–":"noin 1335–Kuollut","1335–Female":"1335–Kuollut","–1374":"–1374","1335–1392":"1335–1392","1360–1397":"1360–1397","1360–1440":"1360–1440","1378–Male":"1378–Kuollut","1380–1428":"1380–1428","–1383":"–1383","–1415":"–1415","1317–Male":"1317–Kuollut","1322–Female":"1322–Kuollut","1440":"1440","1374":"1374","1383":"1383","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1